{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_genesis_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414219767/1927061001/0733.xml":{"full_text":"m BMITAIH HERALD\nNews of the World\nBy Associated Press\nAverage Daily Circulation For\nWeek Ending A Q A Q\nJune 4th\nESTABUSHED 1870\nNEW BRITAIN, CONNECTICUT, FRIDAY, JUNE 10, 1927. THIRTY-TWO PAGES\nPRICE THREE CENTS\n1\n1 Uj\n1.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK BRIGHT\nINDUSTRIAL EXPERT SAYS,\nIN FORECAST FOR COUNTY\nHealthy Upward Swing\nin Fall Predicted at\nManufacturers' An\nnual Meeting.\nKelley Says \"Dry\" Law\nHas Helped Workers-\nNew Britain Men Elect\ned to Office.\nImproved industrial and business\ni conditions in Hartford county are\nanticipated for the fall by Thomas J.\nKelley, manager of the Manufac\nturers' association of Hartford coun\nty, which held its annual meeting at\nthe Farmington Country club last\nnight. Mr. Kelley said: \"The busi\nness outlook indicates production at\nabout its present level into the fall\nwhen a healthy upward swing may\nbe anticipated. There is a prepon\nderance of favorable over unfavor\nable elements. Business funda\nmentals are sound and there are no\nserious production excesses to be\ncompensated for. Artificial stimula\ntion in the meanwhile is warned\nagainst.\"\nIn a statement concerning the ef\nfects of the eighteenth amendment\nto thee constitution, Mr. Kelley de\nclared that the ban on the manu\nfacture and sale of intoxicating li\nquor has helped the working man\nand the employer as well.\nOver 100 Manufacturers Present\nOver 100 manufacturers, repre\nsenting the membership of the asso\nciation, and including a large dele\ngation from this city, attended the\nmeeting and listened to an interest\ning address by Samuel Ferguson,\npresident of the Hartford Electric\nLight Co., who spoke on \"The As\nj peels of Power Production in Con\nnecticut.\" Mr. Ferguson exhibited a\nmap showing the extensive area cov\nered by the electric systems 'of tins\nvicinity which reaches from Canada\nto New Jersey and covers nearly nil\nof New England east of Maine, and\nexplained how, in case of a disaster\nft to the lines or power houses, a hook\nip could be made with neighboring\nsystems with hardly an appreciable\ndelay. He also explained the new\nij mercury power system which his\ncompany is Installing and which is\nexpected to be In full operation be\nJ fore January 1st and which will save\nabout 40 per cent In coal.\nf Howell Cheney, of Cheney Bros.,\nManchester, gave a comprehensive\nreport on legislation relating to\nmanufacturing accomplished 'by the\nlast session of the Connecticut leg\nislation, dwelling especially on the\namendments' to the compensation\nlaws.\nThomas 3. Kelley, manager of the\nI association, gave his annual report.\nXew Britain Men Elected Officers\nFrederick G. Hughes of Brist;!,\nchairman of the nominating com\nI mittee, reported the following names\nfor officers all of whom were elect\ned: President, Charles B. Cook,\nHartford; first vice-president, Arthur\nD. Coffin, Windsor Locks; second\nvice-president, George E. Bean, New\nBritain; treasurer, Phoenix-State\nBank and Trust Co., Hartford; audi\ntors. Arthur W. Fox and Samuel P.\nWilliams; board of managers,\nCharles B. Cook, James L. Goodwin,\nHowell Cheney, Samuel M. Stone,\nCharles B. Whittlesey, Charles L.\nTaylor, Clarence E. Whitney, Charles\nD. Bice, Joseph M. Merrow, Carlisle\nH. Baldwin, Joseph F. Lamb, Clar\nence F. Bennett, F. C. Billings, Alex\nander Harper, Mitchell S. Little,\nStanley S. Gwillim, Arthur D. Cof\nfin, F. N. Wells, Lucius Rossiter,\nClayton R. Burt, Charles L. Tolles\nand George E. Bean. Messrs. Bald\nwin, Lamb and Bennett are New\nBritain men.\nManager Kelley's report was as\nfollows:\nManagecr Kelley's Report\n\"While the business curve of our\nfiscal year reveals fewer peaks and\nhollows than during 1925 and '26,\nit dipped materially during the clos\ning months of last year. After Jan\nuary It maintained a unfform trend\nuntil April when it again reflected\nseasonable recession. It represents\nproduction for actual consumption\nhand to mouth buying. Trade re\nports reveal an excess of goods in\nsome lines in excess of the active de\nmand the results being declining\ncommodity prices and keen comDeti-\n1 tion. The business outlook indicates\nproduction at about its present level\ninto the fall when a healthy upward\nswing may be anticipated. There is\na preponderance to favorable over\nJ unfavorable elements. Business\ni fundamentals are sound and there\nis no serious production excesses to\nbe compensated for. Artificial\n(Stimulation in the meanwhile is\nwarned against.\nt \"Hartford county Industrially is\nlosely allied to the building and\ntitomotive industries both of which\nowed down. This condition was\neflected in nccessory production,\nhere has, however, been no serious\nnemployment in this district dur\nlg the year. On the whole our\nmployes enjoyed fairly steady\nworking conditions. Wage rates\nvaried little, maintaining a liberal\nt relationship to cost of living. Our\nft f.'ietnrios are nt nrntwtnf nnin,.;..\nj.. tll,,uJU(s\n5J.579 hands, a decrease of about\n1,500 from one year ago. Industrial\nj i ariivuy in naruoru county on a man\nnour basis is approximately 80 per\ncent of estimated normal. This Is\nSomewhat above the average for\nother Industrial districts in the state.\n(Continued on Page 19)\n3\nDedication Speaker\nWILLIAM JONES.\nEX-HEAD OF II. S. W. V.\nDEDICATION SPEAKER\nWilliam Jones to Deliver\nAddress at Shaft\nExercises\nWilliam Jones of New York city,\nformer national commander of the\nl'nited Spanish War Veterans, will\nbe the dedication speaker at exer\ncises marking the unveiling of a\nmemorial to Spanish-American war\nveterans, June 25, at Willow Brook\npark.\nEx-Commander Jones will also, be\nthe personal representative of L'nited\nStates Senator Rice W. Means, who\nis the present national leader of the\norganization.\nOthers on the program are Lieut.\nGovernor J. Edwin Brainard, Mayor\nWeld, Rev. J. Leo Sullivan, Rev. Wil\nliam H. Alderson, former National\nCommander Charles W. Newton of\nHartford and Frank P. Fanton.\nThe exercises will take place at\nthe park at 3 o'clock after a street\nparade in which veterans and mem\nbers of patriotic organizations will\ntake part.\nBronze tablets to be placed on the\nmonument will arrive here Saturday,\nMichael Martino of New Haven, who\nis executing the work, has notified\nthe memorial committee. The tablets\nwill depict San Juan hill, the sinking\no the Maine, William MoKinley, the\nSpanish War shield and the honor\nroll.\nHAS NARROW ESCAPE\nDrunken Man Caught on Tracks at\nBridgeport Engineer Stops Train\nJust In Time.\nBridgeport, June 10 (IP) His foot\ncaught in a switch and unable to\nextricate himself and lying prone\nand conscious between the tracks\nof the New Haven railroad an un\nidentified man early today escaped\nby a narrow margin being ground\nto pieces by a New York freight\ntrain about 500 yards west of the\nlocal station.\nThe engineer of the train noticed\nthe prostrate man and applied the\nbrakes. Ho succeeded In bringing\nhis train to a stop with the cow\ncatcher but a few feet from the\nman.\nThe man was removed to the\nemergency hospital where the doc\ntors found that he was stupefied by\nliquor.\nREAL SUMMER WEATHER\nN'ew York Reports 83 Degrees at 1\no'clock Tills Afternoon Cooler\nTomorrow, Is Prediction.\nNew York, June 10 (UP) New\nYork's weather continued an upward\ntrend in temperature today, reach\ning 83 degrees at 1 p. m.\nThe lowest reading in the local\noffice of the U. S. weather bureau\nfor the day was 06, registered at 6\na. m.\nShowers were forecast for tonight\nto be followed by cooler weather\nSaturday. No hints on what the\nweather would be on the 13th, the\noccasion for the public reception to\nColonel Charles A. Lindbergh in\nNew York, could be secured.\nThe advent of summer into the.\nmetropolis began yesterday when the\nmercury reached SI, the second\nhighest reading of the year, at 1\np. in.\nSaw Husband Killed, Now\nSees Her Daughter Die\nOmaha, Neb., June 10 (IPI Mrs.\nMabel E. McNally. who was at\nLangley field. Va., when her hus\nband was killed in the crash of the\nairship Roma in 1922, yesterday\nstood by the bedside of her daugh\nter, Margaret. 0. and watched her\ndie, the victim of an automobile\naccident.\nMargaret was struck by a car as\nshe was hurrying to a neighbor\nhood store to buy groceries. Mrs.\nMcNally's husband -had been com\nmissioned to write a book on the\nconstruction, and the scientific and\ntechnical advances of the Roma.\nHis wife saw the machine when It\ncrashed.\nc\nBURGLARS CAUGHT\nIN TRECTOP HUT\nPolice Puzzled by Mysterious\nVoices But Get Their Prey\nMODERN TARZANS BAGGED\nTwo Boys, Missing From Home For\nSeveral Days, Found Domiciled In\nLeaf; Haunt High Up in Willow\nBrook Park Woods.\nPerched In an improvised hut atop\na high hemlock tree near the so\ncalled gypsy trail in the wooded sec\ntion south of Willow Brook park,\nEdmund Ference, aged 17, of 223\nGlen street, and a 15-year-old com\npanion, who have been away from\ntheir homes for the past several\ndays and nights while living after\nthe fashion of tree dwellers, were\ntaken Into police custody late yes\nterday afternoon on the charge of\nburglary, this bringing to an end a\nhunt that started early this week\nwhen the police received informa\ntion that the young suspects were\ncamping out in the woods beyond\nthe Shuttle Meadow club. In police\ncourt chambers this morning, Judge\nHungerford committed the younger\nboy to the State School for Boys at\nMeriden and suspended execution\nof the commitment. In police court,\nFerence was sentenced to Cheshire\nreformatory.\nFor the past few days, Sergeants\nO'Mara and McAvay have made trips\nto the camp but failed to find the\nyouths. The tent, which they ad\nmitted having stolen from Peter\nMack of Pond street, was well\nequipped with cooking utensils, an\nalarm clock to arouse them early In\nthe morning that they might do\ntheir fishing in a nearby pond be\nfore daybreak, bread, pressed ham,\ncoffee, milk and all the ether ne\ncessities for a comfortable stt-y. The\nfirst day the police inspected the\ncamp, tinfoil off candy bars was\nstrewn about the ground, indicating\nthat sweets were on the menu.\nHear Mysterious Voices\nTiring of being successfully elud\ned, Sergeants O'Mara and McAvay\nobtained information that the youths\nwere frequenting the woods beyond\nWillow Brook park, and it was\nplanned to surprise them yesterday.\nArriving at the gy psy trail, the po\nlicemen heard voices but could see\nnobody on account of the thick\nbrush. Listening attentively, they\ndecided to charge, a pit from whiob\nit was thought the voices were\nemanating, but as Sergeant McAvay\nran from one side and Sergeant\nO'Mara beat the brush from the\nother, they were startled to find that\nthey not only failed to raise their\nquarry, but the sound of the voices\ndied away and the woods were as\nstill as death.\n\"Certainly the ground did not\nopen up and swallow them,\" Ser\ngeant O'Mara deduced. \"No, but\nwhere are they?\" Sergeant McAvay\nasked. They did not know, as they\nstood there debating their dilemma,\nthat in the perch high up in the\ntree a short distance from them,\nwere crouched the young burglars\nwho had sighted Sergeant McAvay\nas he started around the pit prior\nto launching the charge. Every\ninch of the ground about the pit was\nsearched but no trace of anything\nwas found, and then, Just as the de\ntectives were about to abandon the\nhunt, Sergeant O'Mara noticed a\nshort stick leaning against a hem\nlock tree.\nImprovised Ladder is Clue\nAlthough never an enthusiastic\nlover of the great outdoors except\nas represented by the athletic field,\nthe sergeant realized that the stick\ndid not grow against the tree. Some\none must have put It there, and on\nlooking more closely, he saw that\nthe bark of the lower trunk had\nbeen scraped as if by the shoes of\nclimbers. Stepping back that he\nmight obtain a better view of the\ntree top, he saw the hut, securely\nfastened to the topmost limbs, and\nthe mystery of the voices was\nsolved.\nWithin a few minutes of the\nfinding of the stick, the policemen\nhad the youths on the ground and\na short time later, recovery was\nmade of the stolen goods that had\nnot been consumed. Several hid\ning places were pointed, out to the\npoliceman by the youths, one of\nthem being covered by stones which\nhad been carried, apparently with\ngreat effort, for a considerable dis\ntance before they were placed in\nposition to hide the loot. The hut\ncontained some stolen articles, also.\nAccording to Sergeant McAvay's\ntestimony in court, the boys admit\nted the theft of the tent, the burg\nlary at Fred Zelenfs store at 221\nGlen street on June 6, the burglary\nat Morris Silver's soda water estab\nlishment at 16S Greenwood street\non May 2S, and the burglary at the\nWillow Brook Park tool house early\nthis week. Ference cut the glass in\nZelenfs store, which is next to his\nhome, and carried off the loot. The\ndoor at Silver's place was forced and\nsoda water taken, while overalls\nand other articles of wearing\napparel, basketballs and like equip\nment valued at approximately $25\nwere taken from the tool house. The\npair also took a truck out of the\ntool house and drove It around the\npark for no particular reason other\nthan deviltry, according to their\nstatement to the police.\nFish and Roum Woods\nEvery morning during their\nperiod of freedom from restraint\nthey fished when they pleased and\nroamed the woods, they told the\npolice. Their time was their own and\nthey did with It what they pleased,\nrealizing, of course, that It was only\na matter of time before they would\nbe apprehended. They spent some\n(Continued on Page 26.)\nHELEN WILLS DEFEATS\nMRS MALLORY EASILY\nCalifornia Girl Stages Come-Itack\nand Expert See Her Greater\nThan Ever.\nBeckenham, England, June 10 (JP)\nHelen Wills eliminated Mrs. Mol\nla Mallory from the Kent county\nlawn tennis championships today.\nThe former American champion de\nfeated the present title holder 6-0,\n6-1.\nHelen Wills' crushing defeat of\nMrs. Molla Mallory, eight times\nwinner of the American women's\nchampionship, today convinced ob\nservers that the 21 -year-old Cali\nfornia girl has come back to great\ner heights than ever.\nShe has now run up the remark\nable record of winning 24 of her\nlast 25 games in the Kent county\ntournament, having eliminated the\nSouth African girl, \"Billie\" Tap\nscott, yesterday in two love sets.\nOn her present form, which Eng\nlish critics say even outdoes some\nof the former spectacular perform\nances of Suzanne Lenglen, Miss\nWills probably will be a strong\nfavorite to win the British cham\npionship at Wimbledon the last of\nthis month.\nA comparison of Miss Wills'\npresent play with that of her Brit\nish rival, Kitty McKane Godfree,\nthe Wimbledon tltleholder, is pos\nsible through Miss Ryan, who\nforced Mrs. Godfree to three sets\nbefore losing today but who was\ndefeated last week in straight sets,\n6-2, 6-2, by Miss Wills.\n127 WILL GRADUATE\nFROM NORMAL SCDOOL\n27\nWho Will Receive\nDiplomas Live in\nThis City\nTwenty-seven members of New\nBritain State Normal school grad\nuation class of 127 students are\nNew Britain girls, according to the\nlist announced.\nThey are the Misses Frances Bel\nkin, Hilda H. Bessoff, Alice M. Brat\nton, Carolyn E. Braunstein, Sara E.\nConfer, Margaret IS. Conway, Flor\nence E. Freedel, Viola H. Glaser,\nDoris E. Greene, Margaret M. Hart,\nAlice L, Hatney, Hildcgarde Haus\nman, Roso Mllberg, Gertrude Hlnch\nliffe, Bessie Kalmanowitz, Eleanor\nC. Kelley, Frances M, Kerber, Ros\nL. Kirshnlt, Bessie Koplowltz, Elva\nMcKirdy, Elizabeth Poppel, Kath\norine M. Regan, Helen M. Shanahan,\nJulia Suski, Grace G. L'nkelbach,\nSophie Wesker, and Mary A. White.\nOf the remainder there are 12\nfrom Bristol, one from Plainville,\nand one from Berlin.\nThe names of girls whose homes\nare outside of New Britain follow:\nElena C. D'Agostino, Forestville;\nDorothy E. Allport, Bristol; H. Eliz\nabeth Anderson, West Hartford;\nElizabeth T. Barry, Plymouth; Anne\nE. Beaucor, Bristol; Lydia C. Bishop,\nMeriden: Helen Bjornberg, Wood\nstock; Florence M. Bolgcr, Water\nbury; Dorothy A. Brecker, Hartford;\nMary E. Brown, Enfield (Thomp\nsonville); Agnes Burnell, Torring\nton; Bernadette R. Campbell, Mid\ndletown; Adele E. K. Carlson, Attle\nboro, Mass.; Katherine M. Carr,\nTorrlngton; Priscilla A. Carrington,\nBristol; Clara M. Carter, Meriden;\nGrace C. Corbin, Suffield; Loretta\nK. Critchley. Bristol;' Ruth E. Dahl\nstrom, Essex; Mildren E. Dawson,\nHartford; Ruth D. Dombroske.\nMeriden: Marcella C. Drennan. Say\nbrook; Margaret A. Dwyer, Waler\nbu ry.\nDorothy K. Dyer, Norfolk; Blanch\nA. Silver, Hartford; Mabel G. Fish\ner, Meriden; Elizabeth M. Fitzger\nald, Meriden; Ruth J. Flynn, Hart\nford; Helen P. Balinski. Naugatuck;\nRuth Feley, Hartland; Katherine V.\nFlaherty, Waterbury; Alice Fore\nman, Hartford; Helena K. Geffken,\nMiddlefield; Doris M. Gibney, Ber\nlin; Mildred K. Kilmartin, Water\nbury, Antoinette M. Giunta, Hart\nford; Mary A. Griffin, Meriden; An\nna J. Henley. Torrington; Doris M.\nHeffernan, Bristol.\nCatherine Henderling. Bristol;\nMary B. Hovanesian. Hartford;\nDorothea Hughes. Middletown;\nHelen C. Hurtado, Plainville; Tearl\nK. Jandreau. Enfield; Helen B.\nKidney, Middletown: Freda A.\nKovarsky, Hartford; Catherine\n(Continued on Pae 10)\nLong Jail Term for\nDriving While Drunk\nHartford, June 10 (IP) The first\ntrial of the June term of the su\nperior criminal court was held to\nday when Andrew Columbia, 32. of\nBridgeport was presented before\nJudge Avery charged with operating\nan automobile while under the in\nfluence of liquor, fourth offense,\nand with driving without an opera\ntor's license.\nJudge Avery found him guilty and\nsentenced him to six months on the\nfirst count and ninety days on the\nsecond.\nDRUNKEN DRIVER JAILF.D\nMeriden, Juno 10 (P) Harold\nH. Roraback of 535 Zlon street,\nHartford, was fined $100 and sen\ntenced to jail for ten days in the\npolice court today when he pleaded\nguilty to driving a heavy truck\nwhile drunk. Ho was arrested here\nlast night.\nTHE WEATHER\ncw Britain and vicinity:\nProbably showers tonight;\nSaturday generally fair and\ncooler.\nSOVIETS EXECUTE\nMNTYPRISONERS\nThis Is Their Reply to \"Open\nTransition to Terrorism\"\nENGLAND SHOCKED AT NEWS\nOne of Those Put to Death Was\nEnglishman Great Britain For\nmally Denies Having Secret Spies\nin Russia.\nMoscow, Russia, June 10 (IP)\nExecution of twenty persons as a\nreply to the \"open transition to ter\nrorism\" by opponents of the Soviet\nregime is announced in an official\ncommunique published today.\n\"In view of the open transition to\nterrorism and destructive struggle\nby monarchist and white guardist\nelement, acting from abroad, on in\nstructions and with funds from for\neign intelligence services,\" the com\nmunique says, \"the collegium of the\nstate political department parsed\ndeath sentences at its session on\nJune 9 on twenty persons, and the\nsentences have been carried out.\"\nMoscow, June 10 (UP) Twenty\nmonarchist white guards and spies\nalleged to have been in the pay of\nforeign intelligence services, princi\npally Great Britain, have been exe\ncuted, M. Menjinski, chife of the\nSoviet political police, announced to\nday. Englishman Included.\nThose executed included an Eng\nlishman and two Russian princes.\nMenjinski alleged that somo of\nthose executed attempted to take the\nlives of four Soviet government\nheads, including G. V. Tchitcherin,\nforeign minister, A. I. Rykov, presi\ndent of the union council of people's\ncommissaries, and M. Stalin and\nBukharin.\nThe Englishman, Sidney Riley, al\nleged to have been a spy, and an\nother man, George Elvengrcn, who\nwas also executed, attempted to kill\nTchitcherin and others upon their\nreturn from Genoa, the police chief\nsaid. He alleged that they were\ntravelling at the expense of the Brit\nish government.\nThe executions were made, Men\njinski announced, because those who\nreceived the death sentence had\nbeen found \"working upon orders\nwith finances of foreign intelligence\nservices\" with a view to beginning\na \"terroristic and destructive strug\ngle\" against the Soviet government.\nAlleged British .Agents.\nThree of those executed were al\nleged to have been agents or spies\nfor British Charge D'Affaires Hodg\nson Vladi'mar Evrelnow, Nicola\nKoropenko, and Sergei Mazurenkol;\ntwo others. Malevich Malevsky and\nAlevander Skalsky, were alleged to\nhave been in the British intelligence\nservice, the latter as an agent; and\nSolomon Gurevich was alleged to\nhave attempted to take the lives of\nStalin, Rykov, and Bukharin.\nThe two princes executed were\nPrince Dologorukov and Prince Mes\ncherskl. England Is Shocked.\nLondon, Juno 10 (IP) British offi\ncials were shocked today by the an\nnouncement in Moscow of the exe\ncution of 20 persons charged with\nanti-Soviet activities, Including fur\nnishing Information to the British\ndiplomatic mission in Moscow. The\nmission returned to London last\nnight, following the recent rupture\nof Anglo-Soviet relations.\nIt was emphatically denied at\nDowning street that the British mis\nsion in Moscow had had any rela\ntions of this nature with Russia.\nForeign office officials reiterate that\nin breaking off relations with the\nSoviets, the British government was\nactuated fcy no hidden or ulterior\nmotives and had no intention of\n(Continued on Page 25)\nBOSTON BOOK CLERK IS\nGUILTY UNDER STATE LAW\nConvicted of Selling Sinclair's Latest\nNovel, \"Oil,\" Which Is Held\nAs Improper.\nBoston, June 10 UPI John\nGritz. book store clerk, today was\nfound guilty of selling a book,\n\"Oil,\" \"tending to corrupt the\nmorals of youth,\" within the mean\ning of the Massachusetts statute\nforbidding sale of obscene litera\nture. Upton Sinclair, author of the\nbook, arrived in Boston two days\nago to fight the case.\nJudge William H. Sullivan of the\nmunicipal court, who reserved de\ncision on the case yesterday in or\nder that he might read the book,\ntoday fined Gritz. clerk In one of\nthe largest of the Boston book\nstores, $100 for violating the law.\nGirtz appealed.\nSeveral Boston booksellers with\ndrew the volume from their shelves\nvoluntarily after It became known\nthat the police regarded it as \"im\npure.\" Sinclair had declared that he and\nnot the book clerk should have\nbeen prosecuted and announced, in\nevent of conviction, that he intend\ned to make a test sale in the city.\n\"Oil\" was the latest of a long\nseries of works, magazines and\nnovels, which have been banned in\nthis city.\nSinclair later complained that\nthe judgment was rendered with\nout giving him an opportunity to\nexplain the book and its motive.\nHe declared that he was not even\ntold what words or phrases were\nobjected to and that no account\nwas taken of passages modifying\nthose which were condemned.\nHe announced his intention of\nhiring a hall for a free public\nmeeting next Monday morning\nwhen he will read from Hamlet,\nthe Bible and \"Oil.''\nWASHINGTON ON EDGE AS CRUISER\nCARRYING LINDBERGH HEARS PORT;\nBERLIN HEAPS HONORS ON OTHERS\nChamberlin and Levine\nPresented With City's\nHonorary Plaque\nSpend Time Visiting\nAirplane Factories.\nFliers Change Plans and\nWill Go Directly to Other\nEuropean Cities, Meet\ning Wives in Prague\nJune 17.\nBerlin, June 10 (IPl Through\nstreets lined with cheering noon-day\ncrowds, Clarence Chamberlin and\nCharles Levine drove to Rathaus to\nday, accompanied by American Am\nbassador Schurman to receive fur\nther honors in recognition of their\nsensational non-stop flight from\nN'ew York to Germany.\nMounting the imposingly high\nstaircase, they were greeted by Lord\nMayor Boess, who was surrounded\nby uniformed ushers bearing wands\nsurmounted by the coat of arms of\nthe Berlin municipality.\nAfter being presented to the bor\nough mayors, the president of the\nborad of aldermen and other digni\ntaries, the fliers and the ambassador\nsigned the city's \"Golden Book.\"\nThen they were escorted into the\nbanquet hall to be greeted with a\nmangnificent rendition of the \"Star\nSpangled Banner\" by Berlin's fa\nmous symphony orchestra.\nAt the conclusion of the luncheon,\nthe lord mayor announced that the\nthoroughfare leading to TempeLhof\ner air field would henceforth be\nknown as Columbia Slrasse after\nthe trans-Atlantic plane.\nHe then bestowed upon the three\nguests the city's honorary plaque,\nwhich is usually reversed for dis\ntinguished citizens of Berlin.\nPluns Changed.\nThe plans of Chamberlin and Le\nvine underwent several modifica\ntions today.\nFirst, they will not fly to Bremen\nto meet their wives, as they had\nconsidered doing; Instead the women\nwill join their husband at Prague,\nthe capital of Czecho-Slovakia.\nMrs. Chamberlin and Mrs. Levine\nwill debark from the liner Berlin\nat Bremen June 17. where they will\nbe the guests of the Lufthansa air\nlines at a \"festival breakfast.\"\nThey will fly to Berlin, leaving\nBremen at eleven o'clock and ar\nriving in the Tenipelhofer air field\nat 2:00 p. m where they will have\nluncheon in the air field restaurant.\nThen they will leave in a plane for\nPrague at 4:00 p. m., arriving In the\nevening to join their famous hus\nbands. A wtreles message from the\nsteamer Berlin rrcetved at the\nAmerican embassy reports that both\nwomen arc happy and that they are\nbeing given great attention. The\ncaptain turned his cabin over to\nMrs. Chamberlin while Mrs. Levine\nhas cabin No. 1 adjoining.\nChamberlin and Levine will be In\nVienna from June 12 to 15. going to\nPrague on the 16th. Today they ac\ncepted an invitation from the Polish\ngovernment to visit Warsnw, but the\ndate i.i yet to he fixed. They would\nalso like to include Budapest. Hun\ngary, in their itinerary but are not\nsure whether they will do so.\nCheered at Factory.\nChamberlin and Levine, trans\nAtlantic aviators, had a real \"bus\nman's holiday\" this forenoon, motor\ning to Johnnlsthal and inspecting\nthe Rohrbach and Seioniens-Halske\nair craft factories.\nGiving the slip to all the newspa\npermen, the Americans left the em\nbassy at an early hour, and by their\nappearance at the two factories\nstopped productions there. The\nskilled workman laid down their\ntools, cheered the fliers and then\ncrowded around for autographs.\nLate this afternoon Chamberlin\nand Levine were due to Inspect the\nAlbatros 'Works, where war-time\nplnnos were manufactured.\nThe visitors found that the con\nstruction of mtnl plnncs has been\nconsiderably simplified by Ihe ex\nperts of the Ttohrhnch concern.\n\"It is the construction of the fu\nture.\" Chbmbrrlin said \"but at pros-f-nt\nthe cost of production is too\nhigh for us In the Vnited States.\nWhen we can turn them out like\nFords well, we shall see.\n\"Yes. metal planns arc more dur\nable, but not nccessnrilv safer. The\nmotors we saw tit the Siemens fac\ntory promise to rank with the best\nwe have yet seen, and it is only re\ncently that the manufacture of air\ncooled motor began 1n Germany.\"\nChamberlin told the newspaper\nmen he thought that although Ger\nmany was handicapped by the peace\ntreaty conditions as to the size of\nnlancs she was allowed to manufac\nture, she was making such progress\nwith the smaller models that this\nmight turn \"to the great disadvant\nage of the people who forced her\nto do it.\"\n\"It's like Pellanea's case.\" he said,\nreferring to the designer of the trans\nAtlantic monoplane Columbia. \"He\nhad to work on a small scale, be\ncause he only had small capital, but\nhe has the best understanding of\nanybody of the flow of air about a\nmachine, and he makes everything\n(Continued on Page 26.)\nMedal For Lindy\n(NEA Service, Washingvon Bureau)\nOne of the many decorations and\nhonors to be bestowed upon Captain\nLindbergh at 'Washington is the\nSmithsonian Institution's prized\nLangley Medal, for \"acrodromlcs\"\nLindy will be only the fifth recipient\nof this rare award.\nHERE'S PART RADIO\nPLAYS IN BIG EVENT\nPeople All Over Nation\nWill Be \"In\" on Lind\nbergh Celebration\n'New York, June 10 (UP) Ar\nrangements for the broadcasting of\nN'ew York's welcome to Colonel\nCharles Lindbergh on Monday were\nannounced today by tli3 National\nBroadcasting company. Ihe parade\nand welcome is expected to begin at\n11 a. m., eastern daylight saving\ntime, and continue until 4 o'clock in\nthe afternoon.\nWKAF and \"WJZ of the National\nEroadcasting company, and munici\npal station WNYC will share the\nbroadcasting, together with an exten\nsive hookup throughout the east and\nmiddlewcst. As in the case of tomor\nrow's welcome at Washington, an\nnouncers will be placed at strategic\npoints to report the parade as it\nconies up Broadway fro.n the bat\ntery. The official welcome extended\nLindbergh by Mayor Walker will be\nbroadcast from the steps of City\nHall, as will the ceremony of the\nplacing of a wreath on a monument\nin Madison Square park end the of\nficial welcome of N'ew York state,\nwith Governor Smith presiding, in\nCentral Park.\nWE A F will broadcast the Mer\nchants' association luncheon in hon\nor of Lindbergh Tuesday afternoon,\nwhile bith WNYC and WJZ will put\non the air the official dinner of the\ncity of New York Tuesday evening.\nHere are the high points of\nCharles Lindbergh's \"Path of Koses\"\nthis week-end:\nFriday\n4 p. m. Cape Henry, first sight of\nhomeland in three weeks.\nSaturday\n11- 12 noon Washington Navy\nYard, meet mother.\n12- 1 Three and one-half mile pa\nrade to Washington mon mient.\nl:3u Receive Distinguished Fly\ning Cross from President.\nS Cabinet dinner at White House.\n10 Nationa1! Press clua reception.\n11 Minnesota Society reception.\nSunday\n11 a. m. Church with Coolidges.\n1:15 p. m. Arlington cemetery.\n2:30 Walter Reed hospital, dis\nabled soldiers.\n5 Charles Evans Highes will\npresent U. S. Flag association Cross\nof Honor, on capitol step.s'.\n8:30 Missouri State society recep\ntion. Monday\n7 a. m. National Aeronautic as\nsociation aviators' breakfast.\n8-S:30 Leave for N'e.v York.\nTRANSFUSIONS FAIL\nWesterly High School Senior Dies\nToday After Strenuous Effort To\nSave His Life.\nProvidence, R. I., June 10 UPI\nLeo Dotolo, 18, high school senior\nof Westerly, for whom three school\nmates underwent blood transfusions\nin an effort to save his life, died\nthis morning at Westerly hospital.\nFive more schoolmates were await\ning call to give their blood when the\nyouth died.\nDotolo became ill last month on\nthe eve of final examinations and\nwas operated on for appendicitis.\nWhen his condition became worse\nphysicians asked for volunteer! for\nblood transfusion.\nMrs. Lindbergh Leaves\nTrain at Baltimore\nand is Met By Presi\ndent's Auto to Take\nHer to Washington.\nDestroyer Meets Memphis\nat Sea Craft 176 Miles\nFrom Virginia Capes\nThis Morning At Cape\nHenry at 4 p. m.\nU. S. S. Memphis, June 10 (By\nWireless to the' Associatjd Press)\nThe first home contact for Col.\nCharles A. Lindbergh, New York to\nParts flyer, occurred at 6:05 a. m,\ntoday when the destroyer Hum\nphreys met the scout cruiser Mem\nphis at sea.\nThe vessels met 250 miles off the\ncoast. The destroyer took ihnsH\nmovie films, made of the aviator\nauring me voyage and a bag of of\nficial mall which she is to carry to\nNew York. The destroyer is expect\ned to reach N'ew York law today.\nScars U. S. Shore\nWashington, June 10 OP) Ths\ncruiser Memphis with Charles A.\nLindbergh aboard, was 176 nautical\nmiles off the Virginia capes .at 8\no'clock this morning and was mak\ning 22 knots an hour. Vice Admiral\nBurrage informed the navy depart,\nment.\nThe vessel is due off Cape Henry\nat 4 p. m.\nComing By Auto.\nMrs. Evangeline Lindbergh, moth,\nor of the famous flier, broke her rail\njourney from Detroit to Washingou\ntoday at Baltimore ani will be\nbrought here from that city this\nafternoon in a White House auto\nmobile. -j\nMrs. Lindbergh will be the guest\nof Mr. and Mrs. Coolidge at the tem\nporary White House on Dupont Cir.\ncle.\nThe president is sending one of\nhis aides to Baltimore to meet Mrs.\nLindbergh, who went to a hotel there\nalter leaving the train.\nReady In Washington\nWashington, June 10 VP) Wash,\nington i6 prepared to honor tomor\nrow with one of its greatest welcom\ning ceremonies in history the heroio\nNew York to Paris flyer. Colonel\nCharles A. Lindbergh.\nThe first taste of the admiration\nof the American people for his epio\n(light, however, is to be given the\n25 year old pilot on the last stretch\nof his voyage from Europe late to\nday when the navy dirigible Los An.\ngeles and 60 army ani navy air.\nplanes, together with a convoy of\nsix destroyers, are on their way to\nmeet the cruiser Memphis as she\nrounded the Virginia capes. The\ncruiser was scheduled to pass the\ncapes at 4 o'clock this afternoon.\n.Mother Waiting\nMeanwhile, a proud mother, Mrs.\nEvangeline Lindbergh, a Detroit\nschool teacher, will be waiting in\nWashington the triumphal return of\nher son to extend to him her heart\nfelt greeting. Mrs. Lindbergh quietly\nleft Detroit late yesterday by train.\nShe and Colonel Lindbergh are to b\nthe guests of President and Mrs.\nCoolidge at the temporary Dupont\nCircle White House during the av\niator's stay in Washington.\n90 Planes In Parade.\nTomorrow as the cruiser slowly\nsteams up the Chesapeako Bay and\nPotomac river another afiay of air\ncraft, one of the largest concentra\ntion of flying machines ever gathered\nin this country, approximately 90\nai my, navy, commerce and post of\nfice department airplanes, together\nwith more than a score of civilian\nplanes, will escort the aviator to tha\nWashington Navy Yard il, ck where\nlie will disembark.\nThe national capital alone is to\ngive America's official welcome lo\nColonel Lindbergh, it has been de\ncided. Welcome From President\nOutside of the roar of airplane\nmotors and the familiar hand signals\nof pilots, the trans-Atlantic flyer will\nreceive no welcoming greeting until\nPresident Coolidge and a brilliant\narray of government officials, dip\nlomats and fellow famous aviators\nextend their tributes on his arrival\nat Washington.\nIn deference to the wishes of\nPresident Coolidge to have the first\nwelcome in Washington, Virginia\nwill not even extend a reception to\nthe flyer as Lindbergh passes along\nher coast, although Governor Byrd\nand hundreds of the state's resident\nwill embark in boats to cruise along\nside the Memphis to catch a gllmpss\nof him. Governor Byrd previously\nhad planned to board the Memphis\nat the capes.\nTo Drop Uniform\nThe dropping of a package of\nmessages and his Missouri National\nGuard uniform, with the l ew spread\neagles of a colonelcy which he will\ndon for his reception tomorrow, from\nthe dirigible Los Angeles on ths\nMemphis' decks is to bo practloally\nhis only contact with his homeland\ntoday.\nBut upon landing at Navy Yard\nat noon tomorrow, if the Memphis\nadheres to the program, the youthful\n(Continued on Page it)","height":"25368","width":"19364"}}
